Here is data:

active:b,email:s,id:i,name:s,role:s;V1=true,V2=user,V3=admin,V4=false,V5=moderator;V1,alice.smith@example.com,1,alice_smith,V3;V1,bob.jones@example.com,2,bob_jones,V2;V1,carol.white@example.com,3,carol_white,V5;V4,dave.brown@example.com,4,dave_brown,V2;V1,eve.davis@example.com,5,eve_davis,V3;V1,frank.miller@example.com,6,frank_miller,V2;V4,grace.wilson@example.com,7,grace_wilson,V5;V1,henry.moore@example.com,8,henry_moore,V2;V1,iris.taylor@example.com,9,iris_taylor,V3;V4,jack.anderson@example.com,10,jack_anderson,V2

Answer these questions about the data above:
Q: How many users are there in total?
Q: How many users have the role 'admin'?
Q: How many users have the role 'moderator'?
Q: How many users are active?
Q: How many users are inactive?

content.text:
I'll help you analyze this data. I'll first parse the data and then answer each question systematically.

Let me break down the data structure:
- Columns: active (boolean), email (string), id (integer), name (string), role (string)
- Mappings: V1=true, V2=user, V3=admin, V4=false, V5=moderator

I'll use Python to process this data and answer the questions.

input.content:
# User data processing script

data = '''active:b,email:s,id:i,name:s,role:s;V1=true,V2=user,V3=admin,V4=false,V5=moderator;V1,alice.smith@example.com,1,alice_smith,V3;V1,bob.jones@example.com,2,bob_jones,V2;V1,carol.white@example.com,3,carol_white,V5;V4,dave.brown@example.com,4,dave_brown,V2;V1,eve.davis@example.com,5,eve_davis,V3;V1,frank.miller@example.com,6,frank_miller,V2;V4,grace.wilson@example.com,7,grace_wilson,V5;V1,henry.moore@example.com,8,henry_moore,V2;V1,iris.taylor@example.com,9,iris_taylor,V3;V4,jack.anderson@example.com,10,jack_anderson,V2'''

# Value mappings
mappings = {
    'V1': True,
    'V2': 'user',
    'V3': 'admin',
    'V4': False,
    'V5': 'moderator'
}

# Parse the data
rows = data.split(';')[2:]  # Skip header and mappings
users = []

for row in rows:
    values = row.split(',')
    user = {
        'active': mappings[values[0]] == True,
        'email': values[1],
        'id': int(values[2]),
        'name': values[3],
        'role': mappings[values[4]]
    }
    users.append(user)

# Answer the questions
total_users = len(users)
admin_users = sum(1 for user in users if user['role'] == 'admin')
moderator_users = sum(1 for user in users if user['role'] == 'moderator')
active_users = sum(1 for user in users if user['active'])
inactive_users = sum(1 for user in users if not user['active'])

print(f"Total users: {total_users}")
print(f"Admin users: {admin_users}")
print(f"Moderator users: {moderator_users}")
print(f"Active users: {active_users}")
print(f"Inactive users: {inactive_users}")
